Abraham, after he had dwelt ten years in Canaan, took Hagar to wife, of whom in the eighty-sixth year of his age he begot his son Ishmael, Gen. xvi. 15, 16, it appears that he went directly from Mesopotamia to canaan, and that he nowhere fixed any settled habitation till he came to Canaan. Moreover, whether he had obtained that kingdom by force or entreaty, he would not so soon have deserted it, especially when he was constrained by famine to undertake a journey to Egypt3 nor would the sacred writers have neglected to give some hints of a passage so considerable, and which would have tended so much to the glory of the Jews.
